Hey CodinGamer! Your contribution has unfortunately not been moderated on time and will temporarily be removed from the system... But no worries! You can republish it anytime to give it another chance! :)

Appropriate as an Easy puzzle (it could get challenging in some programming languages where parsing might be needed).

Cases
* How's your day going? (test): Please change "like more than 200" to "like more than", and "years old" to "200 years old" (so that there's a line which begins with a digit but the whole line is a string).

* "The World Ends" (test): Please delete the trailing newline in the input.

* Please add a pair of cases where all the following types of values appear in the input:
   â€¢ A positive integer
   â€¢ A negative integer
   â€¢ An integer 0
   â€¢ A positive float
   â€¢Â A negative float
   â€¢ A float 0 (with one or more decimal places)
   
   For each type above (excluding integer and float 0), include the following four magnitude categories (the number of digits shown below EXCLUDE decimal places in the case of floats):
   â€¢ 2-5 digits
   â€¢ 6-15 digits
   â€¢ 16 digits and the absolute value is less than 2**53
   â€¢ 17-99 digits
   â€¢ 100-200 digits
   
   That makes 4 non-zero types x 5 magnitudes + 2 zero types = 22 combinations in total.
   
   For each of the 22 combinations, include two scenarios:
   1. A clean numeric value (e.g. 3.14)
   2. A numeric value followed by a space and additional characters (e.g. 3.1415 is a delicious pie)
   
   That means [[n]] (number of elements) should be at least 44 in each of the new cases. In addition, the output should not be -1 for the new cases.

i think the upper constrain for [[n]] is not stated on the constrain.... the actual constrain are:
- the string length of any element of the array is lower than 200, and
- the array's size is higher than 1

[[n]] can be higher than 200, due to:
if you think of an array of 200 elements and the array is [1,2,3,..., 200], then the maximum length of one element of the array is 3.... 

i think the upper limit for [[n]] is important due to, when i solved this puzzle i had to check the test cases sizes to know if this puzzle needed an optimized algorithm or a brute force one.

While reviewing the last pair of cases, I noticed that applying the float() function to some of the numbers doesn't preserve the decimal part, e.g.

>>> float("-2020015469854121.054005")
-2020015469854121.0
>>> float("-202001546985412.054005")
-202001546985412.06
>>> float("-2020015469854.054005")
-2020015469854.054
>>> float("-202001546985.054005")
-202001546985.05402
>>> float("-20200154698.054005")
-20200154698.054005 # finally matches

That may explain why the decimal places disappear in some of the "numeric value + string" input lines.

-2020015469854121
